Assignment - Data Driven Business

Niels Eenink

18 oktober, 2021

The following video shows how traditional marketing slowly turns into data driven marketing. Looking at data from a marketing perspective, it can be used to make predictions about what a customer wants and what they are willing to pay for it. Also, by collecting data like location a rough prediction can be made what other people may like in the same area.

What features define a data driven business?

According to At Internet(N.D.) a data driven business is defined as followed: When a company employs a data-driven approach, it means it makes strategic decisions based on data analysis and interpretation. A data-driven approach enables companies to examine and organise their data with the goal of better serving their customers and consumers."

Examples of data driven companies are: Microsoft, Netflix, Amazon Prime Video, Uber, Coca Cola, Socrata, etc. All these companies use the data they collect from processes or customers to make decisions on all levels (from strategic to operational).

What are the important features of a data culture?

According to Carl Anderson and Micheal Li form TechCrunch (2017) these are important features of a data culture:

  • The same data cant be on different places, one central place is necessary. Obviously this data needs to be of high quality and easy to find.
  • There needs to be a so called data dictionary where everyone can see what which data means.
  • Everyone can access the data, dashboards and outcomes.
  • Everyone needs to know what they are doing. This is done by the data dictionary and prper training for everyone.
  • The reports need to be used! Trust the data and algorithms, dont be afraid of this making your job obsolete, it only supports you to do your job better!

What are the transformation steps towards a mature data driven business?

Looking through a heap of scientific articles about maturity models for data driven businesses I couldnt find a real standard.

Data competency maturity model Stages of the data competency maturity model Cech, Spaulding and Cazier (2018)

Maturity Model for Data-Driven Manufacturing Weber, Knigsberger, Kassner and Mitschang (2017)

Unfortunately R Markdown doesnt display these, but the links are clickable if you want to have a look.

I used a model and axplanation form Zencos, written by St.Jeor, Matz and Murphy (2019).

The Analytics Maturity Model

  1. Chaotic
  • The typical company is dependent on spreadsheets and ad-hoc analysis. Everything is a one-off, so rarely do tasks go beyond one person doing work in a single spreadsheet.
  1. Repeatable
  • A companys actions move from ad hoc spreadsheet reporting to descriptive analyses of the past. Managers capture a broader view of their processes and better understand the big picture. A more data-driven approach allows managers to streamline the business and cut out unnecessary costs from the sales process.
  1. Standardized
  • The data is made available across departments and more accessible for everyone.
  1. Integrated
  • The company aligned to standards to be more strategic. In Level 4, the chief executives and the other leadership teams want to use data across the enterprise. One of the chief executives spearheads the effort to move the organization forward using data as the key to understanding the sales pipeline and serving customers better. They begin to build out a dedicated analytics team.
  1. Optimized
  • The company has fully implemented a data-driven approach to the business decision process. The executive team includes firmly defined and established roles for a chief analytics officer (CAO) and/or chief data officer (CDO).
